  "body": "# Rationale\r\n\r\nUsing the environ `STOP_BEFORE_STAGE` is super useful for debugging, but another use case is when you want the entire sequence to finish then stop. The specific use case that I have is:\r\n\r\n1. Create instance that on startup will start erigon and run.\r\n2. Wait for erigon to finish a full sync cycle\r\n3. Upload the data so other instances can use this new snapshot\r\n4. Shutdown instance\r\n\r\nI have a setup where a lambda will startup the snapshot instance every day and it takes only a few hours to process 24 hours of changes, so I don't want to run this instance 24 hours a day.\r\n\r\n# Implementation\r\n\r\nThis can be implemented in 2 ways:\r\n1. Rename the `Finished` stage to `Finalize` and change `Finished` to a noop that can be used to know when an entire cycle has finished (ref: https://github.com/ledgerwatch/erigon/blob/6371cd7b5b0c4701a6c0586a8b70d3de4ce1bb00/eth/stagedsync/default_stages.go#L328)\r\n2. Implement the ability to shutdown at a specific block. This is much more complex, but has other useful benefits. This would allow a user to put in a block number in the cli/environ and no headers from a block number greater than this number will be processed and shuts down at sed block number.\r\n\r\nI can see `#2` having other useful use cases, but `#1` is far more easy to implement.\r\n\r\nI'm willing to write up a patch for either one, I just want direction on which one would be preferred (I vote `#1` due to it's simplicity).",
